.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aEPUB and EPDF available Open Access under CC-BY-NC-ND licence. Until recently, higher education in the UK has largely failed to recognise gender-based violence (GBV) on campus, but following the UK government task force set up in 2015, universities are becoming more aware of the issue. And recent cases in the media about the sexualised abuse of power in institutions such as universities, Parliament and Hollywood highlight the prevalence and damaging impact of GBV. In this book, academics and practitioners provide the first in-depth overview of research and practice in GBV in universities. They set out the international context of ideologies, politics and institutional structures that underlie responses to GBV in elsewhere in Europe, in the US, and in Australia, and consider the implications of implementing related policy and practice. Presenting examples of innovative British approaches to engagement with the issue, the book also considers UK, EU and UN legislation to give an international perspective, making it of direct use to discussions of 'what works' in preventing GBV.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSchool violence. 0aWomenxViolence against. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Violence in Society.2bisacsh1 aAnitha, Sundari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnitha, Sundari, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavy, Zowie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaldson, Anni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurbach, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenton, Rache